Evaluating Categorical Predictions¶

Here I am going to evaluate a categorical predictions based on a dataset called "Invistico_Airline"


This data given by an airline organization. The actual name of the company is not given due to various purposes that's why the name Invistico airlines.
The dataset consists of the details of customers who have already flown with them. The feedback of the customers on various context and their flight data has been consolidated.

Data Cleaning & Exploration¶

In [70]:
# Drop incomplete records
df = df.dropna().reset_index(drop=True)
In [71]:
# Replace values with 1 else 0
df['satisfaction'] = df['satisfaction'].replace({'satisfied':1,'dissatisfied':0}).astype(int)

df['Gender'] = df['Gender'] .replace({'Female':0,'Male':1}).astype(int)

df['Customer Type'] = df['Customer Type'] .replace({'disloyal Customer':0,'Loyal Customer':1}).astype(int)

df['Type of Travel'] = df['Type of Travel'] .replace({'Personal Travel':0,'Business travel':1}).astype(int)

Exclude the class_matrix for now .¶

# One-hot encode class identifiers
class_one_hot = pd.get_dummies(df['Class'], prefix='Class_').astype(int)

# Filtering to get just the class dummy columns
class_columns = [col for col in class_one_hot.columns if col.startswith('Class_')]
class_matrix = class_one_hot[class_columns]
df = df.drop('Class', axis=1)

Model Assessment and Selection¶

Set up the full design matrix X, this time include the calss_matrix, and a constant.¶

Finally bind the outcome to it and ensure it's the first column of the resulting dataframe.¶

In [74]:
# Grab relevant features on the heat map above
gender = df['Gender']
customer_type = df['Customer Type']
type_of_travel = df['Type of Travel']
flight_distance = df['Flight Distance']
seat_comfort = df['Seat comfort']
inflight_wifi = df['Inflight wifi service']
inflight_entertainment = df['Inflight entertainment']
checking_service = df['Checkin service']
cleanliness = df['Cleanliness']
departure_delay = df['Departure Delay in Minutes']

# Design matrix
X = pd.concat([
        gender,
        customer_type,
        seat_comfort,
        type_of_travel,
        flight_distance,
        inflight_wifi,
        inflight_entertainment,
        checking_service,
        cleanliness,
        departure_delay,
        class_matrix
], axis=1)

# Add a constant to the feature matrix for statsmodels
X_const = sm.add_constant(X)

# Get full dataset together 
YX_const =  pd.concat([df['satisfaction'],X_const],axis = 1)

Create a validation set (75%) and test set (25%).¶

Ensure the rows of the full dataset selected for each set are chosen at random.¶

In [75]:
# Split data into validation and test (75:25)

# Calculate 25% of the dataset size
num_samples = YX_const.shape[0]* 25 // 100

# Generate a list of all row IDs
row_ids = list(range(YX_const.shape[0]))

# Randomly select 25% of the row IDs
selected_row_ids = random.sample(row_ids, num_samples)

# Subset to create validation and test
YX_const_test = YX_const[YX_const.index.isin(selected_row_ids)] # the randomly chosen 25% goes to test-set
YX_const_val = YX_const[~YX_const.index.isin(selected_row_ids)] # the remaining 75% is our validation set

Using a dictionary, define three candidate models in terms of the columns of the design matrix involved in each.¶

The first model is the homogeneous probability model; the second has have all covariates except the classes; the third uses all the columns.¶

In [76]:
# Define predictors for each model variant
predictors = {
    'a': ['const'],
    'b': [col for col in X_const.columns if not col.startswith('Class_')],
    'c': X_const.columns.tolist()
}
In [77]:
y = YX_const_val['satisfaction'] # Target variable

# Define K for cross validation
K = 5

# Setup the KFold cross-validation
kf = KFold(n_splits=K, shuffle=True)

# Initialize a dictionary to store Brier scores
scores = {key: [] for key in predictors}

# Initialize dictionaries to store scores (e.g. Brier score)
brier_scores = {key: [] for key in predictors}
aic_scores = {key: [] for key in predictors} 

for key, cols in predictors.items():
    
    for train_index, test_index in kf.split(YX_const_val):
        
        # Split into train and test according to the folds 
        X_train, X_test = YX_const_val.iloc[train_index][cols], YX_const_val.iloc[test_index][cols]
        y_train, y_test = y.iloc[train_index], y.iloc[test_index]
        
        # For each fold split, fit the model
        model = sm.Logit(y_train, X_train).fit()
                
        # Predict probabilities
        y_pred_prob = model.predict(X_test)

        # Calculate Metric
        brier_score = brier_score_loss(y_test, y_pred_prob)
        brier_scores[key].append(brier_score)
        aic_scores[key].append(model.aic)

        # (If you pick a classification metric, you have to use a decision threshold)
        # Convert probabilities to binary predictions (assume simple >0.5 probability as threshold)
        y_pred_binary = (y_pred_prob > 0.5).astype(int)
        
        print(model.summary())
        
# Calculate and print the average scores
results = []
for key in predictors.keys():
    average_brier_score = np.mean(brier_scores[key])
    print(average_brier_score)
    average_aic_score = np.mean(aic_scores[key])
    results.append({
        'Model': key,
        'Average Brier Score': average_brier_score,
        'Average AIC': average_aic_score
    })

# Convert results to DataFrame for nicer display
results_df = pd.DataFrame(results)
results_df

For each simulation, generate a predicted probability for the test-set satisfactions.¶

In [81]:
# Initialize an array to store predictions from each simulation
predictions = np.zeros((n_simulations, YX_const_test.shape[0]))

# Generate predictions for each simulation
for i in range(n_simulations):
    beta_simulation = simulated_betas[i]
    log_odds = np.dot(YX_const_test[[col for col in YX_const_val.columns if col!= 'satisfaction']], beta_simulation)
    probabilities = logistic_sigmoid(log_odds)
    predictions[i] = probabilities

For the first 20 assessments in the test-set, plot the posterior distirbution of the probabilities.¶

In [82]:
true_labels = YX_const_test['satisfaction']

# Calculate posterior median and the prediction interval for each of the first 10 observations
posterior_medians = np.median(predictions, axis=0)
lower_bounds = np.percentile(predictions, 2.5, axis=0)
upper_bounds = np.percentile(predictions, 97.5, axis=0)

# Plotting with the adjustments for the 90% prediction interval to be shown with red lines
fig, axes = plt.subplots(4, 5, figsize=(25, 16))

for i in range(20):
    ax = axes[i // 5, i % 5]
    # Histogram of simulated probabilities for observation i
    ax.hist(predictions[:, i], bins=30, color='skyblue', edgecolor='white', alpha=0.7)
    
    # Draw a line for the decision boundary 
    ax.axvline(x=0.5, color='red', linestyle='-', linewidth=1)
    
    # Draw a thick solid black line at the true label position
    true_label_position = 0 if true_labels.iloc[i] == 0 else 1  # Determine the position based on the true label
    ax.axvline(x=true_label_position, color='black', linestyle='-', linewidth=1)
    
    # Add posterior median
    ax.axvline(x=posterior_medians[i], color='blue', linestyle='-', linewidth=1)
    
    # Marking the 90% prediction interval with red lines instead of shading
    ax.axvline(x=lower_bounds[i], color='red', linestyle='-', linewidth=1, label='95% Prediction Interval' if i == 0 else "")
    ax.axvline(x=upper_bounds[i], color='red', linestyle='-', linewidth=1)
    
    ax.set_xlim(-0.1, 1.1)
    ax.set_title(f'Observation {i+1}')
    if i == 0:  # Add legend to the first subplot only to avoid repetition
        ax.legend()

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
